  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering crimes)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n4. Key Regulatory Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\nThese statutes and regulations:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Create criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to implement anti-money laundering programs\n- Mandate suspicious activity reporting\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment for individuals and organizations involved in money laundering activities.",
